-- ── TRACK 6: TAILWIND DEEP DIVE ──────────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Tailwind Core Concepts — The Utility-First Philosophy\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nTailwind CSS takes a radically different approach to styling: instead of writing semantic CSS classes that describe WHAT something is, you compose utility classes that describe HOW it looks. This "utility-first" philosophy has changed how teams build UIs.\n\nR-Learn''s entire interface is built with Tailwind. Understanding it deeply means you can modify, extend, and build on this codebase effectively.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The Tailwind Philosophy\n\n```html\n<!-- Traditional CSS approach -->\n<div class="course-card">...</div>\n/* course-card sits in a .css file */\n/* .course-card { background: white; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; } */\n\n<!-- Tailwind approach -->\n<div class="bg-white border border-gray-200 rounded-xl p-6">...</div>\n<!-- All styling inline, no CSS file needed -->\n\n<!-- Benefits:\n  - No context switching between HTML and CSS files\n  - No naming problem (no "is this card? component? section?")\n  - No dead CSS (PurgeCSS removes unused utilities)\n  - Consistent spacing, colors, typography via design tokens\n  - Responsive, hover, focus states built in\n  - Easy customization via tailwind.config.js\n-->\n```\n\n## 3. Configuration & Customization\n\n```javascript\n// tailwind.config.js\nmodule.exports = {\n  content: [\n    "./index.html",\n    "./src/**/*.{js,ts,jsx,tsx}",  // Files to scan for class names\n  ],\n  darkMode: "class",  // or "media" for system preference\n  theme: {\n    // Override defaults\n    screens: {\n      sm: "640px",\n      md: "768px",\n      lg: "1024px",\n      xl: "1280px",\n      "2xl": "1536px",\n    },\n    // Extend defaults (add to, don''t replace)\n    extend: {\n      colors: {\n        brand: {\n          50:  "#eff6ff",\n          100: "#dbeafe",\n          500: "#3b82f6",\n          600: "#2563eb",\n          700: "#1d4ed8",\n          900: "#1e3a8a",\n        },\n        // Add as many custom colors as needed\n      },\n      fontFamily: {\n        sans: ["Inter", "system-ui", "sans-serif"],\n        mono: ["Fira Code", "monospace"],\n      },\n      borderRadius: {\n        "4xl": "2rem",\n      },\n      animation: {\n        "fade-in":    "fadeIn 300ms ease-out both",\n        "slide-up":   "slideUp 300ms ease-out both",\n        "shimmer":    "shimmer 1.5s infinite",\n      },\n      keyframes: {\n        fadeIn:  { from: { opacity: "0" }, to: { opacity: "1" } },\n        slideUp: { from: { transform: "translateY(16px)", opacity: "0" } },\n        shimmer: { from: { backgroundPosition: "-200% 0" }, to: { backgroundPosition: "200% 0" } },\n      },\n      spacing: {\n        "18": "4.5rem",\n        "88": "22rem",\n        "128": "32rem",\n      },\n    },\n  },\n  plugins: [\n    require("@tailwindcss/forms"),       // Better form styling\n    require("@tailwindcss/typography"),  // Prose styling\n    require("@tailwindcss/line-clamp"),  // Text truncation\n    require("@tailwindcss/aspect-ratio"),\n  ],\n};\n```\n\n## 4. Complete Utility Reference\n\n```html\n<!-- === LAYOUT === -->\n<div class="container mx-auto px-4">          <!-- Centered container -->\n<div class="flex items-center justify-between gap-4">  <!-- Flexbox -->\n<div class="grid grid-cols-12 gap-6">         <!-- CSS Grid -->\n<div class="relative z-10">                   <!-- Positioning -->\n<div class="sticky top-0">                    <!-- Sticky -->\n<div class="fixed inset-0">                   <!-- Full screen -->\n\n<!-- === SPACING === -->\n<div class="p-4">         <!-- padding: 1rem -->\n<div class="px-6 py-3">   <!-- x: 1.5rem, y: 0.75rem -->\n<div class="m-auto">      -- margin auto -->\n<div class="space-y-4">   <!-- children: mt-4 except first -->\n<div class="divide-y">    <!-- children: border-top except first -->\n\n<!-- === SIZING === -->\n<div class="w-full max-w-md">  <!-- Full width, max 28rem -->\n<div class="h-screen">          <!-- 100vh -->\n<div class="size-12">           <!-- width: height: 3rem (new) -->\n<div class="aspect-video">      <!-- 16:9 -->\n<div class="aspect-square">     <!-- 1:1 -->\n\n<!-- === TYPOGRAPHY === -->\n<h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight text-gray-900 dark:text-white">\n<p class="text-base text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">\n<span class="text-sm font-medium text-blue-600 uppercase tracking-wider">\n<p class="line-clamp-3">        <!-- Truncate to 3 lines -->\n<p class="truncate">             -- Single line ellipsis -->\n\n<!-- === COLORS === -->\n<div class="bg-blue-50 text-blue-900">     <!-- Light blue background -->\n<div class="bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-purple-600">  <!-- Gradient -->\n<div class="text-transparent bg-clip-text bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-cyan-600">\n\n<!-- === BORDERS === -->\n<div class="border border-gray-200 rounded-xl shadow-md">\n<div class="ring-2 ring-blue-500 ring-offset-2">  <!-- Focus ring -->\n<div class="divide-y divide-gray-100">            <!-- Dividers between children -->\n\n<!-- === TRANSITIONS & ANIMATIONS === -->\n<div class="transition-all duration-200 ease-in-out">\n<div class="hover:scale-105 transition-transform">\n<div class="animate-spin">      <!-- Loading spinner -->\n<div class="animate-pulse">     <!-- Skeleton loading -->\n<div class="animate-bounce">    -- Notification indicator -->\n\n<!-- === INTERACTIVE STATES === -->\n<button class="hover:bg-blue-700 active:scale-95 focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-blue-500\n               disabled:opacity-50 disabled:cursor-not-allowed">\n<div class="group hover:shadow-xl [&>img]:group-hover:scale-110">\n\n<!-- === DARK MODE === -->\n<div class="bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100">\n<div class="border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700">\n```\n\n## 5. Building the R-Learn Card\n\n```html\n<!-- A complete course card in Tailwind -->\n<article class="group bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 border border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-700\n                rounded-xl overflow-hidden hover:shadow-lg dark:hover:shadow-gray-900\n                transition-all duration-200 hover:-translate-y-0.5">\n\n  <!-- Thumbnail -->\n  <div class="aspect-video overflow-hidden bg-gray-100 dark:bg-gray-700">\n    <img\n      src="/course-thumb.jpg"\n      alt="Course thumbnail"\n      class="w-full h-full object-cover group-hover:scale-105 transition-transform duration-300"\n      loading="lazy"\n    >\n  </div>\n\n  <div class="p-5 flex flex-col gap-3">\n    <!-- Category & Level -->\n    <div class="flex items-center gap-2">\n      <span class="px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium rounded-full bg-blue-50 text-blue-700\n                   dark:bg-blue-900/30 dark:text-blue-400">\n        Frontend\n      </span>\n      <span class="px-2.5 py-0.5 text-xs font-medium rounded-full bg-green-50 text-green-700\n                   dark:bg-green-900/30 dark:text-green-400">\n        Beginner\n      </span>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- Title -->\n    <h3 class="text-base font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-white line-clamp-2\n               group-hover:text-blue-600 dark:group-hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">\n      HTML5 Fundamentals\n    </h3>\n\n    <!-- Description -->\n    <p class="text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 line-clamp-2">\n      Master the building blocks of the web from scratch.\n    </p>\n\n    <!-- Stats -->\n    <div class="flex items-center gap-4 text-xs text-gray-400 dark:text-gray-500">\n      <span class="flex items-center gap-1">📚 12 modules</span>\n      <span class="flex items-center gap-1">⏱ 10 hours</span>\n      <span class="flex items-center gap-1 ml-auto">⭐ 4.8</span>\n    </div>\n\n    <!-- CTA -->\n    <button class="mt-1 w-full py-2 px-4 bg-blue-600 hover:bg-blue-700 text-white\n                   text-sm font-medium rounded-lg transition-colors duration-150\n                   focus-visible:outline-none focus-visible:ring-2 focus-visible:ring-blue-500\n                   focus-visible:ring-offset-2">\n      Enroll Now\n    </button>\n  </div>\n</article>\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: How does Tailwind keep bundle sizes small in production?**\n> Tailwind uses PurgeCSS (built into the `content` config) to scan all specified files for class names and remove unused utilities from the production build. A typical Tailwind development build is ~4MB; production is usually ~5-20KB. Only classes actually used in your code are included.\n\n**Q: How do you apply the same Tailwind classes to multiple elements without repetition?**\n> Options: (1) Extract to a component (best for React). (2) Use `@apply` in a CSS file to create utility classes: `.btn-primary { @apply px-4 py-2 bg-blue-600 text-white rounded-lg; }`. (3) Use JavaScript to create class string utilities: `const btnBase = "px-4 py-2 rounded-lg font-medium"`. Prefer component extraction over `@apply`.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is the `content` config in Tailwind for?\n2. How do you add custom colors in Tailwind?\n3. What is the difference between `theme.extend` and `theme` override?\n4. How do you apply dark mode styles?\n5. What does `group` class enable?\n6. What is `@apply` and when should you use it?\n7. How do you create a custom animation in Tailwind config?\n8. What does `ring-2` add vs `border-2`?\n9. How do you use responsive prefixes?\n10. What does `line-clamp-2` do?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Pattern | Classes |\n|---------|--------|\n| Responsive | `md:flex lg:grid` |\n| Dark mode | `dark:bg-gray-900` |\n| Hover | `hover:bg-blue-700` |\n| Focus | `focus-visible:ring-2` |\n| Group hover | `group` + `group-hover:scale-105` |\n| Gradient | `bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-600 to-purple-600` |\n| Custom | `tailwind.config.js` extend |\n\nTailwind is the fastest way to build beautiful, consistent UIs. Master the vocabulary of utilities and you can build any design system component rapidly.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l60101';

-- ── TRACK 7: NODE.JS ──────────────────────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Node.js Runtime & Architecture — JavaScript on the Server\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nNode.js is a JavaScript runtime built on Chrome''s V8 engine. It allows JavaScript to run outside browsers — on servers, CLIs, tooling, IoT devices. Node.js is what makes full-stack JavaScript development possible.\n\nNode.js is used by Netflix, LinkedIn, Uber, NASA, and thousands of other companies. It is the foundation for the npm ecosystem (2 million+ packages).\n\n---\n\n## 2. Core Architecture\n\n```\nNode.js Architecture:\n\n┌──────────────────────────────────────┐\n│           Node.js Application         │\n│   (Your JavaScript code)             │\n├──────────────────────────────────────┤\n│              Node.js APIs             │\n│  (fs, http, net, path, crypto, etc.) │\n├──────────────────────────────────────┤\n│       libuv (Event Loop + I/O)        │\n│  Thread Pool | Event Queue | Timers  │\n├──────────────────────────────────────┤\n│         V8 JavaScript Engine          │\n│    (Compiles JS → Machine Code)      │\n└──────────────────────────────────────┘\n\nKey insight: Node.js is SINGLE-THREADED but NON-BLOCKING\n\nSingle thread handles:\n- All JavaScript execution\n- Event loop coordination\n\nlibuv thread pool handles:\n- File system operations\n- DNS resolution\n- Crypto operations\n- Other async I/O\n```\n\n## 3. The Event Loop\n\n```\nEvent Loop Phases (simplified):\n\n1. Timers      → Execute setTimeout/setInterval callbacks\n2. I/O         → Execute I/O callbacks (fs, net)\n3. Idle/Prepare → Internal\n4. Poll        → Wait for new I/O events\n5. Check       → Execute setImmediate callbacks\n6. Close       → Execute close callbacks\n\nMicrotask queues (between each phase):\n  - process.nextTick (highest priority)\n  - Promise callbacks (.then, .catch)\n\nOrder: synchronous → process.nextTick → Promises → timers\n```\n\n```javascript\nconsole.log("1 — synchronous");\n\nsetTimeout(() => console.log("2 — setTimeout 0ms"), 0);\n\nPromise.resolve().then(() => console.log("3 — Promise.resolve"));\n\nprocess.nextTick(() => console.log("4 — process.nextTick"));\n\nconsole.log("5 — synchronous");\n\n// Output:\n// 1 — synchronous\n// 5 — synchronous\n// 4 — process.nextTick  (microtask, before Promises)\n// 3 — Promise.resolve   (microtask)\n// 2 — setTimeout 0ms    (timer phase)\n```\n\n## 4. Node.js Built-in Modules\n\n```javascript\nimport { readFile, writeFile, appendFile, mkdir, stat, unlink } from "fs/promises";\nimport path from "path";\nimport os from "os";\nimport { createHash, createHmac } from "crypto";\nimport { EventEmitter } from "events";\nimport { createServer } from "http";\nimport { pipeline } from "stream/promises";\nimport { createGzip } from "zlib";\n\n// File system\nconst content = await readFile("./config.json", "utf8");\nconst config  = JSON.parse(content);\nawait writeFile("./output.json", JSON.stringify(config, null, 2));\n\n// Path utilities\npath.join(__dirname, "assets", "logo.png");\npath.resolve("./relative/path");\npath.extname("filename.ts");    // ".ts"\npath.basename("/full/path.js"); // "path.js"\npath.dirname("/full/path.js");  // "/full"\n\n// OS info\nos.cpus();           // Array of CPU info\nos.totalmem();       // Total RAM in bytes\nos.freemem();        // Free RAM\nos.platform();       // "linux", "darwin", "win32"\nos.homedir();        // "/home/user"\nos.tmpdir();         // "/tmp"\n\n// Crypto\nconst hash = createHash("sha256").update("password").digest("hex");\nconst hmac = createHmac("sha256", "secret").update(data).digest("hex");\n\n// Environment variables\nprocess.env.NODE_ENV;      // "development", "production"\nprocess.env.PORT;          // Server port\nprocess.env.DATABASE_URL;  // Database connection string\nprocess.exit(0);           // Exit cleanly\nprocess.exit(1);           // Exit with error\n```\n\n## 5. Package Management\n\n```bash\n# npm commands\nnpm init -y                    # Create package.json\nnpm install express            # Install production dep\nnpm install -D typescript      # Install dev dependency\nnpm install -g ts-node         # Install globally\nnpm uninstall package-name     # Remove package\nnpm update                     # Update all packages\nnpm audit                      # Check for vulnerabilities\nnpm audit fix                  # Fix vulnerabilities\n\n# package.json scripts\n{\n  "scripts": {\n    "dev":   "ts-node-dev --respawn src/index.ts",\n    "build": "tsc",\n    "start": "node dist/index.js",\n    "test":  "jest --coverage",\n    "lint":  "eslint src --ext .ts"\n  }\n}\n\n# package-lock.json — commit this!\n# Ensures everyone installs exact same versions\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: Is Node.js single-threaded? How does it handle multiple concurrent requests?**\n> Node.js runs JavaScript on a single thread using an event loop. It handles concurrency through non-blocking I/O and callbacks — when a request triggers I/O (database query, file read), Node.js delegates it to libuv''s thread pool, frees the main thread for other requests, and processes the callback when I/O completes. This is efficient for I/O-bound workloads but poor for CPU-intensive tasks.\n\n**Q: What is the difference between `process.nextTick` and `Promise.then`?**\n> Both are microtasks (run between event loop phases), but `process.nextTick` has HIGHER priority than Promise callbacks — it runs before Promises in the microtask queue. Overusing `process.nextTick` can starve I/O. Generally prefer Promises for async code; use `nextTick` only for internal Node.js APIs.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| V8 | JavaScript engine — compiles JS to machine code |\n| libuv | Event loop and async I/O |\n| Event loop | Single-threaded concurrency mechanism |\n| Non-blocking | I/O operations don''t block main thread |\n| npm | Package manager — 2M+ packages |\n| `process.env` | Environment variables |\n| Modules | `import` (ESM) or `require` (CJS) |\n\nNode.js is JavaScript''s server-side runtime. Its non-blocking I/O model makes it excellent for web APIs, real-time apps, and tooling. Understanding the event loop is essential for writing correct, performant Node.js code.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l70101';

-- ── TRACK 8: EXPRESS.JS ───────────────────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# Express.js Setup & Core Concepts — Building Web APIs\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nExpress.js is the most popular Node.js web framework. It provides a minimal, flexible foundation for building web servers and REST APIs. When companies say they built their backend in Node.js, they almost always mean Express (or a framework built on top of it).\n\nExpress handles routing, middleware, request/response objects, and error handling — the building blocks of any web API.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Setup\n\n```bash\nnpm init -y\nnpm install express\nnpm install -D typescript @types/express @types/node ts-node-dev\n```\n\n## 3. Server Setup\n\n```typescript\nimport express, { Request, Response, NextFunction, Application } from "express";\nimport cors from "cors";\nimport helmet from "helmet";\nimport { json, urlencoded } from "express";\n\nconst app: Application = express();\n\n// === MIDDLEWARE ===\napp.use(helmet());              // Security headers\napp.use(cors({ origin: process.env.FRONTEND_URL }));\napp.use(json());                // Parse JSON body\napp.use(urlencoded({ extended: false })); // Parse form data\n\n// Request logging\napp.use((req: Request, _res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  console.log(`[${new Date().toISOString()}] ${req.method} ${req.path}`);\n  next();\n});\n\n// === ROUTES ===\napp.get("/", (req: Request, res: Response) => {\n  res.json({ message: "R-Learn API", version: "2.0.0" });\n});\n\napp.use("/api/users",   usersRouter);\napp.use("/api/courses", coursesRouter);\napp.use("/api/auth",    authRouter);\n\n// === ERROR HANDLING ===\n// 404 handler\napp.use((req: Request, res: Response) => {\n  res.status(404).json({ error: "Route not found", path: req.path });\n});\n\n// Global error handler\napp.use((err: Error, req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  console.error(err.stack);\n  const status = err instanceof AppError ? err.status : 500;\n  res.status(status).json({\n    success: false,\n    error: {\n      message: err.message,\n      code: err instanceof AppError ? err.code : "INTERNAL_ERROR",\n    },\n  });\n});\n\n// === START ===\nconst PORT = Number(process.env.PORT) || 3000;\napp.listen(PORT, () => {\n  console.log(`Server running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);\n});\n\nexport default app;\n```\n\n## 4. Routing\n\n```typescript\nimport { Router, Request, Response, NextFunction } from "express";\n\nconst router = Router();\n\n// GET all courses\nrouter.get("/", async (req: Request, res: Response) => {\n  const { category, level, page = "1", limit = "20" } = req.query;\n\n  const courses = await CourseService.findAll({\n    category: category as string,\n    level:    level as string,\n    page:     Number(page),\n    limit:    Math.min(Number(limit), 100),\n  });\n\n  res.json({ success: true, data: courses });\n});\n\n// GET single course\nrouter.get("/:id", async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n  try {\n    const course = await CourseService.findById(req.params.id);\n    if (!course) return res.status(404).json({ error: "Course not found" });\n    res.json({ success: true, data: course });\n  } catch (error) {\n    next(error); // Pass to error handler\n  }\n});\n\n// POST create course (admin only)\nrouter.post("/", authenticate, authorize("admin"),\n  async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const course = await CourseService.create(req.body);\n      res.status(201)\n         .header("Location", `/api/courses/${course.id}`)\n         .json({ success: true, data: course });\n    } catch (error) {\n      next(error);\n    }\n  }\n);\n\n// PUT update course\nrouter.put("/:id", authenticate, authorize("admin"),\n  async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      const course = await CourseService.update(req.params.id, req.body);\n      res.json({ success: true, data: course });\n    } catch (error) {\n      next(error);\n    }\n  }\n);\n\n// DELETE course\nrouter.delete("/:id", authenticate, authorize("admin"),\n  async (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    try {\n      await CourseService.delete(req.params.id);\n      res.status(204).end();\n    } catch (error) {\n      next(error);\n    }\n  }\n);\n\nexport const coursesRouter = router;\n```\n\n## 5. Middleware Patterns\n\n```typescript\n// Authentication middleware\nexport async function authenticate(\n  req: Request,\n  res: Response,\n  next: NextFunction\n) {\n  const authHeader = req.headers.authorization;\n  if (!authHeader?.startsWith("Bearer ")) {\n    return res.status(401).json({ error: "No token provided" });\n  }\n\n  const token = authHeader.split(" ")[1];\n  try {\n    const payload = verifyToken(token);\n    req.user = await UserService.findById(payload.sub);\n    next();\n  } catch {\n    res.status(401).json({ error: "Invalid or expired token" });\n  }\n}\n\n// Authorization middleware factory\nexport function authorize(...roles: string[]) {\n  return (req: Request, res: Response, next: NextFunction) => {\n    if (!req.user) return res.status(401).json({ error: "Not authenticated" });\n    if (!roles.includes(req.user.role)) {\n      return res.status(403).json({ error: "Insufficient permissions" });\n    }\n    next();\n  };\n}\n\n// Rate limiter\nimport rateLimit from "express-rate-limit";\n\nexport const apiLimiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 15 * 60 * 1000, // 15 minutes\n  max:      100,              // 100 requests per window\n  message:  { error: "Too many requests", retryAfter: "15 minutes" },\n  standardHeaders: true,     // Return rate limit info in headers\n  legacyHeaders:  false,\n});\n\nexport const authLimiter = rateLimit({\n  windowMs: 60 * 60 * 1000,  // 1 hour\n  max:      10,               // 10 login attempts per hour\n  message:  { error: "Too many login attempts" },\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is middleware in Express and how does the middleware chain work?**\n> Middleware is a function with `(req, res, next)` signature. When a request comes in, Express calls each middleware in order. `next()` passes control to the next middleware. If you don''t call `next()`, the request stops there. Middleware can modify req/res, end the request, or pass it along. They stack: logging → auth → validation → route handler → error handler.\n\n**Q: How does Express error handling work?**\n> Error-handling middleware has 4 parameters: `(err, req, res, next)`. When any middleware calls `next(err)` (passing an error), Express skips to the first 4-parameter middleware. Global error handlers should be defined last. All async route handlers need try/catch with `next(error)` — unhandled promise rejections don''t automatically reach error middleware in older Express.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What is middleware in Express?\n2. What does `next()` do?\n3. How do you define route parameters?\n4. What is the difference between `app.use` and `app.get`?\n5. How do you access request body in Express?\n6. What makes an error-handling middleware different?\n7. How do you structure routes into separate files?\n8. What does `helmet()` do?\n9. How do you handle 404 errors in Express?\n10. What is the order of middleware execution?\n\n---\n\n## 8. Lesson Summary\n\n| Concept | Key Point |\n|---------|----------|\n| Middleware | `(req, res, next)` — runs before route handler |\n| Router | `express.Router()` — group related routes |\n| `req.params` | URL parameters: `/users/:id` → `req.params.id` |\n| `req.query` | Query string: `?page=1` → `req.query.page` |\n| `req.body` | Request body (requires `json()` middleware) |\n| Error handler | 4-param: `(err, req, res, next)` — defined last |\n| `next(error)` | Pass to error handler |\n\nExpress is the backbone of Node.js web APIs. Its minimal approach gives you the freedom to structure your application how you want — with the middleware pattern as the core building block.', 25, 1)
WHERE id = 'l80101';

-- ── TRACK 9: REST API DESIGN ──────────────────────────────

UPDATE public.lessons SET content = E'# REST Principles — Designing APIs That Make Sense\n\n---\n\n## 1. Introduction\n\nREST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style for designing web APIs. A RESTful API uses HTTP methods, URLs, and status codes in a standard, predictable way. When you follow REST conventions, your API is intuitive for any developer to use.\n\nBad API design is expensive — it leads to client bugs, breaking changes, and support tickets. Good REST design is a professional skill.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The Six REST Constraints\n\n```\n1. Client-Server Separation\n   → Client and server are independent\n   → Client does not know how server stores data\n   → Server does not know how client displays data\n\n2. Stateless\n   → Each request contains ALL information needed\n   → Server does not store session state\n   → Authentication token in every request header\n\n3. Cacheable\n   → Responses must declare if they can be cached\n   → Use Cache-Control, ETag, Last-Modified headers\n\n4. Uniform Interface\n   → Standard resource naming (URLs)\n   → Standard methods (HTTP verbs)\n   → Standard status codes\n   → HATEOAS (links to related resources)\n\n5. Layered System\n   → Client cannot tell if it''s talking to server directly\n   → CDN, load balancer, cache can be between them\n\n6. Code on Demand (optional)\n   → Server can send executable code (JavaScript)\n   → Not commonly used in REST APIs\n```\n\n## 3. Resource Design & URL Naming\n\n```\nREST URL Conventions:\n\n✅ Use nouns (resources), not verbs\n  /courses              (not /getCourses)\n  /users/:id            (not /getUser)\n  /courses/:id/modules  (not /getCourseModules)\n\n✅ Plural nouns for collections\n  /courses   (not /course)\n  /users     (not /user)\n  /modules   (not /module)\n\n✅ Lowercase with hyphens\n  /course-categories    (not /courseCategories)\n  /user-profiles        (not /UserProfiles)\n\n✅ Nested resources for relationships\n  /courses/:id/modules          (modules of a course)\n  /users/:id/enrollments        (user''s enrollments)\n  /courses/:id/modules/:mid/lessons  (lessons of a module)\n\n✅ Query parameters for filtering, sorting, pagination\n  /courses?category=frontend&level=Beginner\n  /courses?sort=enrolled:desc\n  /courses?page=2&limit=20\n  /courses?search=html\n\n❌ Avoid verbs in URLs\n  /getUsers → GET /users\n  /createUser → POST /users\n  /deleteUser/123 → DELETE /users/123\n  /activateUser/123 → PATCH /users/123 { active: true }\n```\n\n## 4. HTTP Methods & Status Codes\n\n```typescript\n// Complete RESTful resource design\n\n// COLLECTION routes\nGET    /api/courses          → 200 + array of courses\nPOST   /api/courses          → 201 + created course + Location header\n\n// ITEM routes\nGET    /api/courses/:id      → 200 + course, or 404\nPUT    /api/courses/:id      → 200 + updated course (full replace), or 404\nPATCH  /api/courses/:id      → 200 + updated course (partial), or 404\nDELETE /api/courses/:id      → 204 No Content, or 404\n\n// Status codes cheat sheet\n200 OK             → Successful GET, PUT, PATCH\n201 Created        → Successful POST (include Location header)\n204 No Content     → Successful DELETE, or PUT with no body to return\n400 Bad Request    → Malformed request body or params\n401 Unauthorized   → Not authenticated (no/invalid token)\n403 Forbidden      → Authenticated but not authorized\n404 Not Found      → Resource doesn''t exist\n409 Conflict       → Resource already exists (duplicate email)\n422 Unprocessable  → Validation errors in the request body\n429 Too Many Req   → Rate limit exceeded\n500 Server Error   → Unexpected server error\n503 Unavailable    → Server temporarily down\n```\n\n## 5. Request & Response Design\n\n```typescript\n// Consistent response envelope\n\n// Success response\n{\n  "success": true,\n  "data": { /* the resource */ },\n  "message": "Course created successfully"\n}\n\n// Paginated list response\n{\n  "success": true,\n  "data": [ /* array of resources */ ],\n  "pagination": {\n    "page":       1,\n    "perPage":    20,\n    "total":      156,\n    "totalPages": 8\n  }\n}\n\n// Error response\n{\n  "success": false,\n  "error": {\n    "code":    "VALIDATION_ERROR",\n    "message": "Validation failed",\n    "details": {\n      "email":    ["Must be a valid email address"],\n      "password": ["Must be at least 8 characters", "Must contain a number"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n\n// Example: Create course endpoint\n// POST /api/courses\n// Request body:\n{\n  "title":       "HTML5 Fundamentals",\n  "description": "Master the building blocks of the web",\n  "level":       "Beginner",\n  "category":    "Frontend",\n  "thumbnail":   "https://cdn.rlearn.com/courses/html5.jpg"\n}\n\n// Response: 201 Created\n// Location: /api/courses/abc-123\n{\n  "success": true,\n  "data": {\n    "id":          "abc-123",\n    "title":       "HTML5 Fundamentals",\n    "description": "Master the building blocks of the web",\n    "level":       "Beginner",\n    "category":    "Frontend",\n    "thumbnail":   "https://cdn.rlearn.com/courses/html5.jpg",\n    "createdAt":   "2024-06-01T10:00:00Z",\n    "updatedAt":   "2024-06-01T10:00:00Z"\n  }\n}\n```\n\n## 6. API Versioning\n\n```\nVersioning strategies:\n\n1. URL versioning (most common, most visible)\n   /api/v1/courses\n   /api/v2/courses\n\n2. Header versioning (cleaner URLs)\n   GET /api/courses\n   Accept: application/vnd.rlearn+json; version=2\n\n3. Query parameter versioning\n   /api/courses?version=2\n\nRecommendation: URL versioning\n- Most transparent\n- Easy to test in browser\n- Clear in logs and analytics\n\nVersioning rules:\n- Never break v1 when introducing v2\n- Deprecate old versions with warning headers\n- Support old versions for 6-12 months minimum\n```\n\n---\n\n## 7. Interview Questions\n\n**Q: What is the difference between PUT and PATCH?**\n> PUT replaces the ENTIRE resource — send all fields, missing ones become null/default. PATCH updates only the SPECIFIED fields — send only what changed. If you PATCH `{ email: "new@example.com" }`, only email changes. If you PUT the same, all other fields are wiped. PATCH is idempotent if the update is deterministic.\n\n**Q: What is HATEOAS?**\n> Hypermedia As The Engine Of Application State — responses include links to related resources and available actions. Instead of the client having to know URLs, the API tells it: `"_links": { "self": "/api/courses/html5", "modules": "/api/courses/html5/modules", "enroll": "/api/courses/html5/enroll" }`. GitHub''s API implements this. It makes APIs self-discoverable.\n\n---\n\n## 8. Knowledge Check\n\n1. What does REST stand for?\n2. What HTTP method creates a new resource?\n3. What status code means "created successfully"?\n4. What is the difference between 401 and 403?\n5. What does "stateless" mean in REST?\n6. How should multi-word resource names be formatted in URLs?\n7. What status code should DELETE return on success?\n8. What is API versioning?\n9. What is a 422 status code for?\n10. What is the difference between `/users/1/courses` and `/courses?userId=1`?\n\n---\n\n## 9. Lesson Summary\n\n| Pattern | Implementation |\n|---------|---------------|\n| Collection | `GET /resources` |\n| Create | `POST /resources` → 201 |\n| Read | `GET /resources/:id` → 200/404 |\n| Full update | `PUT /resources/:id` → 200 |\n| Partial update | `PATCH /resources/:id` → 200 |\n| Delete | `DELETE /resources/:id` → 204 |\n| Filtering | `?category=frontend` |\n| Pagination | `?page=1&limit=20` |\n| Versioning | `/api/v1/resource` |\n\nREST design is about consistency and predictability. When you follow conventions, every developer can use your API without reading the documentation — because they already know how HTTP + REST works.', 25, 1)
